  "text": "To prove this, they consider a specific infinite set Y ⊆ ω and then show that it is Σ 1 1 -definable in (M, X). However, their purported Π 1 1 -definition of Y does not work as it actually defines the set Y ∪ (M\\ω). Smoryński makes a similar error in his explicit claim [CITATION_1] Lemma 4.2] that if M is nonstandard and not recursively saturated and (M, X) |= ACA 0 , then ω is ∆ 1 1 -definable in (M, X). We will show in Theorem 2 that this approach is doomed since there are nonstandard models M that are not recursively saturated even though ω is 1 All usages of definable in this paper should be understood as definable with parameters.",
